Install sf

If you are installing sf (or any other package for the first time, use the command âinstall.packages(âsfâ, dep=T)â or the âInstallâ button on the side panel.

Troubleshooting and more info: https://r-spatial.github.io/sf/

is.element('sf', installed.packages())
## [1] TRUE
library(sf)
## Linking to GEOS 3.12.2, GDAL 3.9.1, PROJ 9.4.1; sf_use_s2() is TRUE

At the time of updating my codes, the most recent version of GEOS, GDAL, and PROJ are: GEOS 3.12.2, GDAL 3.9.1, PROJ 9.4.1

Read a shapefile to R

Remember to change the working directory first. The command below reads a MULTIPOLYGON simple feature collection with 323 features and 15 fields

sg_pa = st_read("MP14_SUBZONE_WEB_PL.shp") 
## Reading layer `MP14_SUBZONE_WEB_PL' from data source 
##   `/Users/smu/Library/CloudStorage/Dropbox/ECON627/Lessons/1 Introduction/MP14_SUBZONE_WEB_PL.shp'

table(st_is_valid(sg_pa))
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##     9   314

There are 9 false entries. As a habit you should always check the validity especially if the dataset is downloaded from the Internet.

If there are FALSE entries, use the command st_make_valid() to validate the object.

sg_pa = st_make_valid(sg_pa)
table(st_is_valid(sg_pa))
## 
## TRUE 
##  323

No more invalid entries!

Visualise the shapefile

plot(sg_pa, max.plot = 12)

plot(sg_pa["PLN_AREA_N"])

Save an sf object to the hard drive

In the st_write() function, you can use the âdsnâ (data source name) argument to specify which driver or the file format you need. For example âxxx.shpâ will write the sf object to a shapefile as demonstrated below.

st_write(sg_pa, "MySingapura.shp", delete_layer=T) 
## Deleting layer `MySingapura' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Writing layer `MySingapura' to data source 
##   `MySingapura.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Writing 323 features with 15 fields and geometry type Unknown (any).

The âdelete_layer = TRUEâ argument will overwrite any other file of the same name.

If instead you want to save as a geojson file, use the following command.

#st_write(sg_pa, "MySingapura.geojson")
